WEBVTT

00:01.213 --> 00:01.952
You go ahead.
Have your fun.

00:02.083 --> 00:02.997
[Gasps]

00:03.128 --> 00:04.303
♪

00:04.433 --> 00:06.435
Be my companion.

00:06.566 --> 00:07.871
Claudia: If you're going
to beat Lestat..

00:08.002 --> 00:09.177
This is not a life!

00:09.308 --> 00:11.049
You took my life!

00:11.179 --> 00:12.746
...you have to think
like he does

00:12.876 --> 00:15.009
and then five moves
ahead of that.

00:15.140 --> 00:17.838
She is poisoning Louis
against me.

00:17.968 --> 00:19.274
Claudia:
Kill Antoinette.

00:19.405 --> 00:21.842
We're his slaves,
and I shall free us both.

00:21.972 --> 00:22.843
You have won.

00:22.973 --> 00:24.149
You want to kill him, too.

00:24.279 --> 00:25.628
Finish the game!

00:25.759 --> 00:27.413
Louis:
We were going to kill Lestat.

00:30.285 --> 00:36.857
♪

00:36.987 --> 00:43.646
♪

00:43.777 --> 00:50.566
♪

00:56.485 --> 01:04.102
♪

01:04.232 --> 01:05.929
[Mouse clicking]

01:06.060 --> 01:08.062
[Keyboard clacking]

01:08.193 --> 01:13.459
♪

01:13.589 --> 01:18.942
♪

01:19.073 --> 01:20.161
[Beep]

01:20.292 --> 01:22.859
So...

01:22.990 --> 01:24.687
question.

01:24.818 --> 01:27.734
Can an immortal meet
mortality?

01:27.864 --> 01:31.825
♪

01:31.955 --> 01:35.481
Louis:
Technically, yes.

01:35.611 --> 01:37.178
How?

01:37.309 --> 01:39.572
♪

01:39.702 --> 01:42.096
Several ways.

01:42.227 --> 01:44.446
Starvation.

01:44.577 --> 01:47.362
Deny the body the blood.

01:47.493 --> 01:51.540
Conversely, drink
the blood of the dead.

01:51.671 --> 01:55.936
He told me as much
my first night reborn.

01:56.066 --> 01:58.982
Then, there's fire.

01:59.113 --> 02:03.422
Consume the body with fire
and it can house no spirit.

02:03.552 --> 02:05.641
Decapitation.

02:05.772 --> 02:08.253
He confided that to me
one blood-drunken night

02:08.383 --> 02:11.865
in Baton Rouge.

02:11.995 --> 02:16.391
Theoretically,
it can be done.

02:16.522 --> 02:20.787
But could it be done
by us to him?

02:20.917 --> 02:23.572
Could the children murder
the father?

02:23.703 --> 02:25.748
♪

02:25.879 --> 02:29.796
He was stronger than us,
quicker than us,

02:29.926 --> 02:31.754
in possession
of ancient powers

02:31.885 --> 02:33.669
that had been passed on
to his progeny

02:33.800 --> 02:36.716
only in a diminished form.

02:36.846 --> 02:42.287
Add to the toxic air
a new ever-present paranoia,

02:42.417 --> 02:45.899
and now, you are with us.

02:46.029 --> 02:47.509
We were compelled
to sleep

02:47.640 --> 02:51.121
in the same chamber
together again.

02:51.252 --> 02:52.949
He would have it
no other way.

02:53.080 --> 02:54.995
♪

02:55.125 --> 02:58.216
We would spend our hours
enduring,

02:58.346 --> 03:01.306
with little pretense
of getting along,

03:01.436 --> 03:04.091
locked together in hatred.

03:04.222 --> 03:07.660
He would have it
no other way.

03:07.790 --> 03:11.533
Our only opportunity to plot
would be telepathically.

03:11.664 --> 03:14.710
And Claudia, for reasons
she would not yet divulge,

03:14.841 --> 03:16.843
used our advantage
sparingly.

03:16.973 --> 03:18.801
Knowledge
is the ocean's edge.

03:18.932 --> 03:21.630
I mean, to think it could
somehow be gathered

03:21.761 --> 03:23.545
by a mere 20 volumes.

03:23.676 --> 03:24.981
[Chuckles]

03:25.112 --> 03:28.942
But make no mistake,
Claudia was plotting,

03:29.072 --> 03:31.161
quiet in her deer blind.

03:31.292 --> 03:33.251
[Book slams shut]

03:33.381 --> 03:35.731
A relic before it's even gone
to the print shop.

03:35.862 --> 03:37.603
[Book thuds][Groaning]

03:37.733 --> 03:39.474
♪

03:39.605 --> 03:41.128
[Lestat clicking tongue]

03:41.259 --> 03:43.217
Aww...

03:43.348 --> 03:46.307
There's three of us
you must provide for tonight.

03:46.438 --> 03:51.181
♪

03:51.312 --> 03:54.054
I've had my fill.

03:54.184 --> 03:55.751
[Chuckles]

03:55.882 --> 03:59.755
Louis's never honored
the blood as he should.

03:59.886 --> 04:03.281
Blame the teacher,
not the student.

04:03.411 --> 04:05.544
Lestat de Lioncourt.

04:05.674 --> 04:08.329
♪

04:08.460 --> 04:13.682
179 years
in the Savage Garden.

04:13.813 --> 04:20.472
148 years the blood-drinker,
the bringer of death...

04:20.602 --> 04:23.475
♪

04:23.605 --> 04:25.955
...the deer
come up the trail.

04:27.957 --> 04:29.655
Another approaches.

04:30.264 --> 04:33.180
[Breathing heavily]

04:33.311 --> 04:35.269
[Coughs]

04:39.099 --> 04:41.623
[Wheezing, coughing]

04:45.366 --> 04:46.715
[Gasps]

04:46.846 --> 04:48.369
It's you.

04:48.500 --> 04:49.631
Oh!

04:49.762 --> 04:51.024
Are you
the new postman?

04:51.154 --> 04:52.634
I'm sorry.
I'm sorry!

04:52.765 --> 04:54.288
[Grunting]

04:54.419 --> 04:56.246
Come to deliver letters
of salvation?

04:56.377 --> 04:58.510
I did -- I did not mean
to disturb.

04:58.640 --> 05:01.556
This is a private house,
and we find it disturbing

05:01.687 --> 05:03.950
when things are abandoned
on our doorstep.

05:04.080 --> 05:05.473
You misunderstand.

05:05.604 --> 05:09.172
I-I'm an admirer.
I-I've come seeking help.

05:09.303 --> 05:10.870
Claudia: Hmm.

05:11.000 --> 05:13.568
Well, you came
to the wrong house.

05:13.699 --> 05:16.049
Man: They say that Satan lives
in this house.

05:16.179 --> 05:17.746
But I say it different.

05:17.877 --> 05:23.361
I say angels --
angels live at 1132.

05:23.491 --> 05:25.406
Does anyone know
you came here?

05:25.537 --> 05:28.061
No.
No one, I swear.

05:28.191 --> 05:30.846
I-I live alone,
over on Ursuline.

05:30.977 --> 05:32.239
I'm your neighbor.

05:32.370 --> 05:34.197
Well, send Saint Peter
our regards.

05:34.328 --> 05:36.461
[Snarls]
[Screams]

05:39.942 --> 05:42.728
[Screaming]

05:42.858 --> 05:44.164
[Neck snaps]

05:46.166 --> 05:48.298
[Body thuds]

05:48.429 --> 05:50.257
[Groans, spits]

05:50.388 --> 05:51.867
Claudia:
"Dear sirs and madam..."

05:51.998 --> 05:53.521
Cancer of the blood.

05:53.652 --> 05:56.394
"What is your secret?
Can it be shared?

05:56.524 --> 05:58.700
I have the means to pay you.
I'm dyin'.

05:58.831 --> 06:00.659
The medications aren't taking
and my --"

06:00.789 --> 06:03.531
Enough!

06:03.662 --> 06:06.012
Two in one night.

06:06.142 --> 06:11.234
Dolls, Bibles, letters become
torches and pitchforks.

06:11.365 --> 06:13.498
[Breathing heavily]

06:13.628 --> 06:15.804
We have to leave
this place.

06:15.935 --> 06:18.198
We have to leave
New Orleans.

06:18.328 --> 06:20.766
Clean up the mess
and come to coffin.

06:20.896 --> 06:22.768
We have plans to make.

06:22.898 --> 06:24.987
Louis:
There were plans to make,

06:25.118 --> 06:27.163
but the architect
of those plans was --

06:27.294 --> 06:28.861
Claudia.
Right.

06:28.991 --> 06:32.517
Cold, calculating,
on mission.

06:40.002 --> 06:41.526
I-I interrupted.

06:41.656 --> 06:43.266
Uh...
S-Sorry.

06:43.397 --> 06:44.877
I-I got caught up in it.

06:45.007 --> 06:46.574
You were saying?

06:48.402 --> 06:51.536
[Bell dinging]

06:51.666 --> 06:53.929
Louis: You already have
your plan, don't you?

06:54.060 --> 06:57.846
Claudia: I have a plan,
and it's gonna take both of us.

06:57.977 --> 07:00.240
Maybe start by telling me
the plan?

07:00.936 --> 07:02.024
[Bell dings]

07:02.155 --> 07:04.070
[Brakes screech]

07:08.074 --> 07:10.119
You share a coffin
with him.

07:10.250 --> 07:11.817
I don't talk in my sleep.

07:11.947 --> 07:13.949
You share a heart
with him.

07:14.080 --> 07:15.255
I can cut it off.

07:15.385 --> 07:17.387
No, Louis.
You can't.

07:17.518 --> 07:19.215
You spend an hour
alone with him

07:19.346 --> 07:21.087
and you're breathing
in sync together.

07:21.217 --> 07:24.873
[Heartbeat echoing]

07:25.004 --> 07:28.224
The plan only works
if he's distracted.

07:28.355 --> 07:30.183
I can pretend.

07:30.313 --> 07:33.447
I used to see this woman, Lily,
just to keep appearances.

07:33.578 --> 07:35.231
I can --
He'll know.

07:35.362 --> 07:37.364
It'll only work
if you give in.

07:37.495 --> 07:39.932
Give him all your heart,
and I'll do the rest.

07:40.062 --> 07:41.934
[Bell dings]

07:42.064 --> 07:43.762
[Doors open]

07:43.892 --> 07:45.633
I can't do that.

07:45.764 --> 07:49.071
I'll lose myself in him.

07:49.202 --> 07:52.205
Leave a little shelf
inside there for me.

07:52.335 --> 07:56.209
I'll jump back in and pull you
out before I kill him.

07:56.339 --> 07:58.037
Can you do that
for us, Louis?

07:58.167 --> 08:02.258
[Classical music plays on piano]

08:02.389 --> 08:05.348
Louis?

08:05.479 --> 08:07.699
Yeah, I can do it.

08:07.829 --> 08:13.879
♪

08:14.009 --> 08:16.446
It's best to travel light,
I think.

08:16.577 --> 08:20.450
Reduce our valuables
to a few trunks each.

08:20.581 --> 08:22.888
What about Greece?

08:23.018 --> 08:25.586
Cradle of
Western Civilization.

08:25.717 --> 08:30.373
Sun worshipers,
hot springs.

08:30.504 --> 08:32.550
Those who must be kept.

08:32.680 --> 08:33.812
What was that?

08:33.942 --> 08:35.291
Nothing.

08:35.422 --> 08:37.467
Uh, if I know Italians,
they'll be in Santorini

08:37.598 --> 08:39.469
with their guns out
by the end of the year.

08:39.600 --> 08:44.387
No, we must follow the geese
to Buenos Aires.

08:44.518 --> 08:47.347
Bach.
Always back to Bach.

08:47.477 --> 08:49.131
Bach is beyond you.

08:49.262 --> 08:51.656
Yes, the music
of the master race is...

08:51.786 --> 08:55.181
not made for these
mongrel ears.

08:55.311 --> 08:59.533
You irritate me.
Your very presence irritates me.

08:59.664 --> 09:02.231
I came to make peace with you,
Uncle Les.

09:02.362 --> 09:04.103
[Music stops]Mm.

09:04.233 --> 09:07.193
Sister, daughter, infant death,
you must think me an idiot.

09:07.323 --> 09:08.498
Could you two
please just --

09:08.629 --> 09:11.066
[Speaking French]

09:16.332 --> 09:18.030
Hmm.

09:19.074 --> 09:25.777
♪

09:25.907 --> 09:32.697
♪

09:32.827 --> 09:35.351
I've a present
for you, Lestat.

09:35.482 --> 09:37.223
An idea.
Hmm.

09:37.353 --> 09:39.486
An idea of yours?

09:39.617 --> 09:43.011
It must be
a small gift, then.

09:43.142 --> 09:45.231
A weak man slips a letter
under his door,

09:45.361 --> 09:47.973
and the glorious
vampire Lestat

09:48.103 --> 09:51.759
runs like a rat
to his hole.

09:51.890 --> 09:54.414
It's not fear, but wisdom
that guides our departure.

09:54.544 --> 09:57.373
It's heroic that we've lasted
as long as we have.

09:57.504 --> 09:59.027
Agreed, but...

09:59.158 --> 10:01.160
shouldn't we leave
on our own terms?

10:01.290 --> 10:06.295
Shouldn't we mock the city
like we mock our victims?

10:06.426 --> 10:08.776
You have something in mind,
obviously.

10:08.907 --> 10:10.473
Do nothing different,

10:10.604 --> 10:12.432
settle our affairs,
prepare to leave,

10:12.562 --> 10:14.913
but on our last night,
throw a party.

10:15.043 --> 10:17.698
[Scoffs]
We're pariahs,
sister.

10:17.829 --> 10:20.048
No one's comin' to a party
thrown by freaks.

10:20.179 --> 10:21.354
Precisely.

10:21.484 --> 10:23.051
It's in the dying man's
letter.

10:23.182 --> 10:25.619
They want to know
our secret.

10:25.750 --> 10:28.796
They think we've got
the fountain of youth in here.

10:28.927 --> 10:32.626
They don't know
they're the fountain.

10:32.757 --> 10:35.934
An amusing...

10:36.064 --> 10:38.632
but needful idea.

10:38.763 --> 10:40.286
I guess you're right.

10:40.416 --> 10:42.375
It was just a thought.

10:42.505 --> 10:45.683
♪

10:45.813 --> 10:48.207
The page, Louis.
The page.

10:48.337 --> 10:51.514
♪

10:51.645 --> 10:53.865
Announcer: In the five years
since Adolf Hitler took command

10:53.995 --> 10:55.475
over a people reduced to
despair

10:55.605 --> 10:57.390
by World War defeat
and its aftermath...

10:57.520 --> 10:58.696
They may be nasty
little beasts,

10:58.826 --> 11:01.873
but they do have
excellent tailoring.

11:02.003 --> 11:03.613
Well-dressed
tyrants.

11:03.744 --> 11:07.182
Where have I seen
that before?Hmm...

11:07.313 --> 11:08.575
Well, this idea of yours,

11:08.706 --> 11:11.056
what kind of a party
did you imagine?

11:11.186 --> 11:12.492
Claudia: A ball.[Man sighs]

11:12.622 --> 11:15.451
A lavish,
decadent ball.

11:15.582 --> 11:17.279
To what end?Moviegoer: Shh!

11:17.410 --> 11:19.542
[Announcer continues
indistinctly]

11:21.457 --> 11:25.592
We invite the most beautiful,
the most gluttonous,

11:25.723 --> 11:29.509
seduce a choice few
for a feast to remember.

11:29.639 --> 11:31.293
Hmm.

11:31.424 --> 11:32.904
Shh!

11:33.034 --> 11:38.648
♪

11:38.779 --> 11:40.738
[Claudia giggles]

11:40.868 --> 11:42.827
Buenos Aires,
as fast as we can.

11:42.957 --> 11:44.742
[Hand slapping]

11:44.872 --> 11:47.483
...and its demigod,
Adolf Hitler.

11:47.614 --> 11:49.311
[Grunting]

11:49.442 --> 11:54.534
♪

11:54.664 --> 11:57.102
[Crowd cheering]Man #1: Happy New Year!

11:57.232 --> 12:00.627
Louis: Keep pushing this party,
he's gonna be on to you.

12:00.758 --> 12:02.498
Claudia:
I want him suspicious.

12:02.629 --> 12:04.239
I welcome it.

12:04.370 --> 12:07.112
You're gonna try to kill him
at this party?

12:07.242 --> 12:08.548
There's no "trying."

12:08.678 --> 12:09.941
Mardi Gras is early
this year.

12:10.071 --> 12:12.813
February 6th.

12:12.944 --> 12:14.641
Say it's ridiculous.

12:14.772 --> 12:16.904
That's not how it works.

12:17.035 --> 12:19.298
They plan Mardi Gras balls
a year out,

12:19.428 --> 12:20.995
sometimes
years in advance.

12:21.126 --> 12:25.043
Everyone in costume,
everyone drinking,

12:25.173 --> 12:28.437
chaos in the streets
for an easy escape.

12:28.568 --> 12:30.309
It's not worth
the risk.

12:30.439 --> 12:31.963
[Brass band playing,
people shouting]

12:32.093 --> 12:33.529
Told you.

12:33.660 --> 12:36.489
Although, if we starved
ourselves for a night

12:36.619 --> 12:38.317
or several nights
prior...

12:40.406 --> 12:43.975
...the hunger would be
transcendent.

12:44.105 --> 12:46.499
A meal fit for a king.

12:46.629 --> 12:48.370
Woman in Street: It's over!
I'm through with you!

12:48.501 --> 12:49.676
Man in Street:
Come on, baby!

12:49.807 --> 12:52.070
[Indistinct shouting]

12:52.200 --> 12:53.245
Come here.

12:53.375 --> 12:55.377
-Whoo!
-Fine!

12:55.508 --> 12:57.597
You want the mister
or the missus?

12:57.727 --> 12:59.729
[Fireworks sizzle, squeal]

12:59.860 --> 13:00.992
[Grunts]

13:01.122 --> 13:07.433
♪

13:07.563 --> 13:09.348
For a king.

13:09.478 --> 13:13.178
♪

13:14.527 --> 13:16.877
We're gettin' out, Tom.

13:17.008 --> 13:18.879
Anderson:
Out of New Orleans?

13:19.010 --> 13:20.838
But you just got here.

13:20.968 --> 13:23.144
[Lighter clicks]

13:23.275 --> 13:25.843
Uh, seeing as it's been 17 years
since we've spoken,

13:25.973 --> 13:30.151
what makes you think
I give a corn-peppered shit?

13:30.282 --> 13:33.851
We'd like to engage
your services, Mr. Anderson.

13:33.981 --> 13:36.157
We wanna throw
a Mardi Gras ball.

13:36.288 --> 13:39.682
Pay our respects to society
before moving on.

13:39.813 --> 13:42.033
[Coughs]
Hmm.

13:42.163 --> 13:43.904
Mm. Where to start?

13:44.035 --> 13:47.647
Uh, one, I'm not in
the party-planning business.

13:47.777 --> 13:50.302
Two, it's January.

13:50.432 --> 13:52.478
You're a little bit
behind the gun.

13:52.608 --> 13:54.306
And three...

13:58.832 --> 14:04.751
This is me and your two-tone
daddies circa 1910.

14:04.882 --> 14:06.884
But can you tell me,
little girl,

14:07.014 --> 14:08.668
what's wrong
with this picture?

14:10.844 --> 14:13.499
You didn't have that funny X
on your face back then.

14:13.629 --> 14:16.023
[Chuckles]

14:16.154 --> 14:17.851
Hmm.

14:17.982 --> 14:20.419
I mean, this is
all good and...

14:20.549 --> 14:22.116
sufficiently creepy.

14:22.247 --> 14:23.335
What do you want?

14:23.465 --> 14:24.640
Lestat: I want...

14:24.771 --> 14:26.512
to be Raj.

14:26.642 --> 14:27.992
King of Mardi Gras.

14:28.122 --> 14:30.168
[Laughs]
Him?

14:30.298 --> 14:33.345
[Laughing]

14:33.475 --> 14:35.564
Louis: We know you're on
the committee.

14:35.695 --> 14:40.787
The Committee of Raj is a secret
and sacred group of citizens...

14:43.050 --> 14:44.791
...bound by honor
and tradition.

14:44.922 --> 14:46.314
Get us a price,
get back to us.

14:46.445 --> 14:48.447
These things are planned
years in advance.

14:48.577 --> 14:51.232
Louis, you're a native.

14:51.363 --> 14:53.931
You've expanded
your export business,

14:54.061 --> 14:57.238
shipping coffins
from port back to Europe?

14:57.369 --> 14:59.284
Shipping and manufacturing.

14:59.414 --> 15:00.850
Double dip.

15:00.981 --> 15:03.462
Good margin,
product in high demand.

15:03.592 --> 15:06.160
You lost one of your ships
recently.

15:06.291 --> 15:09.903
Took a torpedo in the rear
from one of the Fritz's U-boats.

15:10.034 --> 15:11.557
Would you like a new one?

15:11.687 --> 15:16.954
♪

15:17.084 --> 15:20.914
Wait, just one question
before I attempt

15:21.045 --> 15:25.484
your no doubt humiliating
and reputation-destroying ask.

15:25.614 --> 15:28.661
♪

15:28.791 --> 15:30.793
Where do you meet the Devil,

15:30.924 --> 15:32.882
and what are the terms
of the agreement?

15:33.013 --> 15:39.541
♪

15:39.672 --> 15:46.244
♪

15:46.374 --> 15:48.463
Louis: The Krewe of Raj
had been three years

15:48.594 --> 15:50.900
in planning
their Mardi Gras theme,

15:51.031 --> 15:52.685
and they abandoned it
within a week

15:52.815 --> 15:55.296
once the Parisian law firm
of Roget and Albert

15:55.427 --> 16:00.084
had transatlantically
wired their bribes.

16:00.214 --> 16:02.129
From the Marais
to the Mississippi,

16:02.260 --> 16:04.871
money flooded the town.

16:05.002 --> 16:07.700
Unavailable vendors
became available.

16:07.830 --> 16:10.746
And the gossip that followed
broke through the levees.

16:10.877 --> 16:14.837
♪

16:14.968 --> 16:17.536
The weird brothers
and their doll-like sister

16:17.666 --> 16:19.451
were coming out.

16:19.581 --> 16:21.453
And the paper ticket
to the event

16:21.583 --> 16:24.586
was a brick of gold
for the insatiably curious.

16:24.717 --> 16:27.198
Lestat: I've chartered us
a plane to Havana.

16:27.328 --> 16:30.244
Three cabins on the SS Dundee
from Havana to Rio,

16:30.375 --> 16:34.466
and two sleeper cars from Rio
to La Reina del Plata.

16:34.596 --> 16:36.729
We'll sell what we no longer
want to Max Simon,

16:36.859 --> 16:38.687
and we'll leave the rest
to the auction house.

16:38.818 --> 16:41.212
We'll need trunks
that'll fit our coffins.

16:41.342 --> 16:42.604
Make sure they have
locks that --

16:42.735 --> 16:44.737
Locks that trigger
from the inside.

16:44.867 --> 16:49.524
♪

16:49.655 --> 16:52.397
It was a masterful month
of preparation.

16:52.527 --> 16:54.573
♪

16:54.703 --> 16:58.751
Daniel: You aimed at the navel,
seduced the seducer.

16:58.881 --> 17:01.319
♪

17:01.449 --> 17:04.191
Louis: By the time we began
our fasting,

17:04.322 --> 17:06.367
Lestat would have told you
the entire endeavor

17:06.498 --> 17:08.369
had been his idea
to begin with.

17:08.500 --> 17:09.936
When is it?

17:10.067 --> 17:12.025
[Rashid speaking indistinctly]

17:12.156 --> 17:13.635
Yeah.

17:13.766 --> 17:15.202
Yes.

17:16.334 --> 17:18.988
♪

17:19.119 --> 17:22.253
We'll go without the blood for
three nights preceding the ball.

17:22.383 --> 17:25.821
At the ball, Louis and I will
be following your leering eye.

17:25.952 --> 17:28.476
Maybe pluck one or two
for ourselves.

17:28.607 --> 17:30.522
We'll ask them if they wanna
be young forever.

17:30.652 --> 17:33.655
And if they say yes, we'll
pin them with one of these.

17:33.786 --> 17:35.570
Hmm.
Amaranth.

17:35.701 --> 17:36.876
Perfection.

17:37.006 --> 17:38.704
We'll invite them
to our home,

17:38.834 --> 17:42.186
we will lock the doors,
shutter the windows, and...

17:42.316 --> 17:44.884
[All chuckle]

17:45.014 --> 17:48.409
And let the flesh
instruct the mind.

17:48.540 --> 17:50.542
Let the flesh
instruct the mind.

17:50.672 --> 17:53.327
Let the flesh
instruct the mind.

17:53.458 --> 17:56.417
Daniel: So, fire?
Behead the bastard?

17:56.548 --> 17:58.332
Louis: She wouldn't tell me
at the time,

17:58.463 --> 18:00.682
as I was slipping back
into old feelings,

18:00.813 --> 18:01.988
as she said I would.

18:02.119 --> 18:03.729
Laudanum and arsenic.

18:03.859 --> 18:05.209
But I would know
soon enough.

18:05.339 --> 18:06.514
Thank you.

18:06.645 --> 18:08.690
Poison the bait
was the game.

18:08.821 --> 18:10.953
Make it appear as if
the flesh was drunk

18:11.084 --> 18:14.000
when, in fact, his victim's
veins were swollen

18:14.131 --> 18:17.525
with a paralyzing brew
of laudanum and arsenic.

18:17.656 --> 18:19.788
Claudia could
taste her freedom,

18:19.919 --> 18:22.139
suffered the hunger
with a cold joy,

18:22.269 --> 18:27.666
matched only by the sun-hot ego
of the vampire king.

18:27.796 --> 18:32.714
And here comes
the Krewe of Raj!

18:32.845 --> 18:34.151
[ Cheers and applause ]

18:34.281 --> 18:37.676
All hail to the Realm of Raj!

18:37.806 --> 18:43.029
♪

18:43.160 --> 18:48.252
♪

18:48.382 --> 18:49.818
Is that a baby?

18:49.949 --> 18:51.516
[Crowd chatters]

18:51.646 --> 18:56.912
[Crowd gasps, screams]

18:57.043 --> 18:58.740
[Laughter]

18:58.871 --> 19:04.572
♪

19:04.703 --> 19:07.923
The ball that followed
was an assault of the senses,

19:08.054 --> 19:10.317
an extravagant
waste of money.

19:10.448 --> 19:12.537
And while Lestat's poor taste
on the float

19:12.667 --> 19:16.149
drove away most every member
of the Raj Committee,

19:16.280 --> 19:18.673
there was plenty of bait
to choose from.

19:18.804 --> 19:21.110
[Indistinct conversations,
lively music playing]

19:21.241 --> 19:24.549
♪

19:24.679 --> 19:27.073
[Heartbeats echoing] The blood was everywhere.

19:27.204 --> 19:30.816
The veins and arteries
of a few hundred hearts

19:30.946 --> 19:33.645
ringing out
like air raid sirens,

19:33.775 --> 19:37.170
drowning out the rhythm section
of the hired band.

19:39.520 --> 19:42.610
I followed Claudia's lead
as best I could,

19:42.741 --> 19:45.918
scouting the rooms
for varietals of death.

19:46.048 --> 19:53.621
♪

19:53.752 --> 19:56.363
Would you like to know
the secret of immortality?

19:56.494 --> 19:58.060
Well, of course,
my dear.

19:58.191 --> 19:59.758
Who wouldn't?

19:59.888 --> 20:02.369
♪

20:02.500 --> 20:04.893
Good seeing you out of uniform,
Chief Bardin.

20:05.024 --> 20:06.765
I think you've mistaken me --Pardon me.

20:06.895 --> 20:08.941
I saw your mask
in the bathroom.

20:09.071 --> 20:11.291
I won't deny,
won't confirm.

20:11.422 --> 20:14.729
You are a man
who appreciates power.

20:14.860 --> 20:18.037
Tell me more,
Mr. du Lac.

20:18.167 --> 20:19.430
Woman #1:
You have been missed

20:19.560 --> 20:21.562
in the Lower Garden,
Mr. Lioncourt.

20:21.693 --> 20:24.609
Woman #2: We heard you'd been
ill all these years.

20:24.739 --> 20:27.612
Pardon me, madams,
is there a history between us?

20:27.742 --> 20:30.354
Uh, the Women's
Opera Society.

20:30.484 --> 20:31.964
Prytania Street?

20:32.094 --> 20:33.835
Well, it has been
over a decade.

20:33.966 --> 20:35.446
Of course. Yes.

20:35.576 --> 20:38.362
You don't appear ill.

20:38.492 --> 20:40.625
Rumors, envy.

20:40.755 --> 20:42.279
Oh.

20:42.409 --> 20:44.846
Now, which one of you did
I pull under the stairs

20:44.977 --> 20:47.719
during that dull lecture
on Don Giovanni?

20:47.849 --> 20:49.242
That would be me.

20:49.373 --> 20:53.290
And that was my late husband
giving the lecture.

20:53.420 --> 20:55.204
And did he talk himself
to death?

20:55.335 --> 20:56.510
Oh.
[Laughs]

20:56.641 --> 20:59.905
[Both laughing]

21:00.035 --> 21:03.604
Your Majesty, I'd like
to introduce you

21:03.735 --> 21:08.566
to the MacPhail brothers,
Matthew and his brother Mark.

21:08.696 --> 21:10.698
Well...

21:10.829 --> 21:12.309
And where are
Luke and John?

21:12.439 --> 21:14.180
[Both chuckle]

21:14.311 --> 21:16.182
♪

21:16.313 --> 21:19.141
[Sniffs]

21:19.272 --> 21:21.796
[Inhales deeply]

21:21.927 --> 21:25.191
Is there rosemary
in your garden?

21:25.322 --> 21:29.543
Uh, yeah...
just below the porch.

21:29.674 --> 21:33.330
Our mother planted a whole
bushel this past summer.

21:33.460 --> 21:34.983
Did she?

21:35.114 --> 21:36.942
[Music ends, crowd applauds]

21:37.072 --> 21:39.074
[Slow music plays]

21:39.205 --> 21:43.470
The king finds himself
suddenly famished.

21:43.601 --> 21:45.298
Would you excuse me?

21:45.429 --> 21:49.302
♪

21:49.433 --> 21:52.131
A cascade of feelings
came over me

21:52.261 --> 21:56.135
as I watched him
sponge up the adoration.

21:56.265 --> 21:58.659
I wanted him dead.

21:58.790 --> 22:02.054
I wanted him all to myself.

22:02.184 --> 22:04.491
The fasting was a mistake.

22:04.622 --> 22:06.754
I wasn't thinking clearly.

22:06.885 --> 22:08.887
♪

22:09.017 --> 22:12.064
Something was off.

22:12.194 --> 22:14.545
Antoinette:
You miserable dog.

22:14.675 --> 22:19.854
♪

22:19.985 --> 22:21.726
Louis: What about a dog?

22:21.856 --> 22:23.597
Claudia: What dog?

22:23.728 --> 22:26.078
You just said something
about a dog.

22:26.208 --> 22:28.994
I said no such thing.

22:29.124 --> 22:31.910
Tom Anderson:
I see you, Louis du Lac.

22:32.040 --> 22:33.477
There's another one.

22:33.607 --> 22:35.609
You're just hungry,
Louis.

22:35.740 --> 22:38.830
You heard what I said just now,
didn't you?

22:38.960 --> 22:41.702
It's the dome.

22:41.833 --> 22:45.967
The architect that built
this place made the US Capitol.

22:46.098 --> 22:47.404
Mm-hmm.

22:47.534 --> 22:49.275
He made it so you could hear
the sniping

22:49.406 --> 22:51.408
and whatnot
across the way.

22:51.538 --> 22:54.149
Calls it
a "whispering gallery."

22:54.280 --> 22:56.195
Course...

22:56.325 --> 22:59.285
how you heard me
over the band...pfft!

22:59.416 --> 23:00.808
It's got to be
one of those tricks

23:00.939 --> 23:04.943
that you and your fag
pederast satanic trio

23:05.073 --> 23:06.597
got in your pocket.

23:06.727 --> 23:10.905
♪

23:11.036 --> 23:12.690
It's a hell of a party!

23:12.820 --> 23:15.214
♪

23:15.344 --> 23:19.348
Do you know the secret
to immortality?

23:19.479 --> 23:21.089
Never get married.

23:21.220 --> 23:22.961
[Both chuckle]

23:23.091 --> 23:25.442
That's a good joke.

23:25.572 --> 23:27.531
And now that you
have your boat...

23:27.661 --> 23:31.970
♪

23:32.100 --> 23:33.798
...don't you want more?

23:33.928 --> 23:39.020
♪

23:39.151 --> 23:44.286
♪

23:44.417 --> 23:48.682
The king's hair
has betrayed the king.

23:48.813 --> 23:50.336
Hmm.

23:50.467 --> 23:54.383
Was that a witticism
from the Duke of Gloom himself?

23:54.514 --> 23:56.342
Hunger's got me
light-headed.

23:56.473 --> 23:58.431
[Music, laughter in distance]

23:58.562 --> 24:05.351
♪

24:05.482 --> 24:12.271
♪

24:12.401 --> 24:14.534
I'm going to miss
this place.

24:14.665 --> 24:21.106
♪

24:21.236 --> 24:23.064
There's not an inch of this city
that wasn't built

24:23.195 --> 24:27.242
from the fierce wilderness
that surrounds it.

24:27.373 --> 24:30.550
Hurricanes, floods, fevers.

24:30.681 --> 24:33.118
♪

24:33.248 --> 24:35.294
The damp climate
on every painted sign,

24:35.424 --> 24:36.948
every stone facade.

24:37.078 --> 24:42.127
♪

24:42.257 --> 24:45.217
High windows,

24:45.347 --> 24:48.568
through which enameled bits
of civilization glitter.

24:48.699 --> 24:53.530
♪

24:53.660 --> 24:59.231
Silhouettes emerging,
wandering out to catch

24:59.361 --> 25:01.320
a silent flash
of lightning.

25:01.450 --> 25:03.888
♪

25:04.018 --> 25:06.107
The silky warmth
of summer rain.

25:06.238 --> 25:10.459
♪

25:10.590 --> 25:12.113
Desperately alive...

25:12.244 --> 25:16.161
♪

25:16.291 --> 25:17.945
...and desperately fragile.

25:18.076 --> 25:22.341
♪

25:22.471 --> 25:25.344
[Chuckles]

25:25.474 --> 25:29.478
The hunger has me too,
it seems.

25:29.609 --> 25:32.699
The boutonnieres
have all been given out.

25:32.830 --> 25:34.440
We're ready when you are.

25:34.571 --> 25:41.534
♪

25:41.665 --> 25:48.628
♪

25:48.759 --> 25:51.326
A last dance
before the feast.

25:51.457 --> 25:53.764
♪

25:53.894 --> 25:55.592
I'd like that.

25:55.722 --> 25:57.463
I'd like that very much.

25:57.594 --> 25:59.813
♪

25:59.944 --> 26:04.122
Louis:
So much would be written about
that grim night in New Orleans,

26:04.252 --> 26:08.866
but not a single mention
of our last hour at Latrobe's,

26:08.996 --> 26:11.825
as if the only crime
unfit to print

26:11.956 --> 26:14.132
took place
on that dance floor.

26:14.262 --> 26:23.576
♪

26:23.707 --> 26:32.977
♪

26:33.107 --> 26:42.508
♪

26:42.639 --> 26:51.909
♪

26:52.039 --> 26:55.652
It was my sole duty
to distract Lestat,

26:55.782 --> 26:57.392
but in his mirrored eyes,

26:57.523 --> 27:00.787
the distraction reflected
back onto me.

27:00.918 --> 27:03.747
And in the dead center
of the whispering gallery,

27:03.877 --> 27:06.663
I lost the thread
to my plotting

27:06.793 --> 27:11.189
and fell once more into
the well with no bottom.

27:11.319 --> 27:14.714
I was his, and he was mine.

27:14.845 --> 27:22.156
♪

27:22.287 --> 27:24.028
[Crowd gasps]

27:24.158 --> 27:27.161
♪

27:27.292 --> 27:29.207
[Indistinct murmurs]

27:29.337 --> 27:36.083
♪

27:36.214 --> 27:37.911
May I finish this dance?

27:38.042 --> 27:40.087
♪

27:40.218 --> 27:41.959
If he'll have you,
sister.

27:42.089 --> 27:48.879
♪

27:49.009 --> 27:50.489
Louis:
We shouldn't do this.

27:50.619 --> 27:53.144
Claudia: Too late.
I've done it already.

27:53.274 --> 27:55.233
When? Who?

27:55.363 --> 27:57.583
Just now.
One of the twins.

27:57.714 --> 27:59.585
He'll be dead on his feet
in an hour.

27:59.716 --> 28:01.630
♪

28:01.761 --> 28:03.502
Ah!
Wake up!

28:03.632 --> 28:10.770
♪

28:10.901 --> 28:17.995
♪

28:18.125 --> 28:20.519
Lestat:
In the 14th century,

28:20.649 --> 28:23.087
in the third arrondissement
of Paris,

28:23.217 --> 28:27.134
on the Rue de Montmorency,
there lived a seller of books,

28:27.265 --> 28:30.529
who found, in an otherwise
regretful purchase

28:30.659 --> 28:34.402
at a private library,
a twenty-page manuscript

28:34.533 --> 28:39.190
written in a text
he could not decipher.

28:39.320 --> 28:42.584
So, he traveled to Spain
to have it translated.

28:42.715 --> 28:44.586
And on his way...[Exhales deeply, clears throat]

28:44.717 --> 28:46.719
Lestat: ...he met a Jewish
converso who told him

28:46.850 --> 28:51.158
he was in possession of the Book
of Abramelin the Mage.

28:51.289 --> 28:53.334
We're all pretty drunk here,
Lestat.

28:53.465 --> 28:55.641
[Laughter]

28:57.643 --> 29:00.951
The bookseller dedicated
the rest of his life

29:01.081 --> 29:03.910
to reproducing the alchemy
within that book,

29:04.041 --> 29:10.221
and one in particular sits
before you all now.

29:10.351 --> 29:12.310
[Gasping]

29:14.616 --> 29:16.444
That's what's in
the punch bowl?

29:16.575 --> 29:20.666
Amrit Ras, Chasma-i-Kausar,

29:20.797 --> 29:22.973
the Philosopher's Stone,

29:23.103 --> 29:24.757
the elixir of life.

29:24.888 --> 29:28.326
[Groans][Laughter]

29:28.456 --> 29:31.198
I drank it
as a young man...

29:31.329 --> 29:33.244
[Chuckles]

29:33.374 --> 29:37.770
...and I recently passed
its powers to my friends here.

29:37.901 --> 29:41.861
Claudia, born 1903.

29:41.992 --> 29:45.604
I drank the water
in 1917.

29:45.734 --> 29:47.562
I'm 36 years old.

29:47.693 --> 29:49.260
[Gasping]

29:49.390 --> 29:54.178
Louis de Pointe Du Lac,
born in 1878.

29:54.308 --> 29:57.485
I drank of the water
in 1910.

29:57.616 --> 30:00.532
I am 61 years old now.

30:00.662 --> 30:05.798
Lestat de Lioncourt,
born 1760.

30:05.929 --> 30:09.933
I drank the waters
in 1794.

30:10.063 --> 30:14.372
180 years old...

30:14.502 --> 30:16.026
this coming November.

30:16.156 --> 30:17.592
Give me that ladle!

30:17.723 --> 30:19.290
[Woman gasps]

30:19.420 --> 30:21.205
Pfft!Ah!

30:21.335 --> 30:22.859
[Lid clatters]

30:22.989 --> 30:24.556
[Ladle clatters]

30:24.686 --> 30:27.646
The bucket's got
a hole in it.

30:27.776 --> 30:29.343
It's empty!

30:29.474 --> 30:31.432
Not for long, Tom.

30:31.563 --> 30:34.566
[Grunting, screaming]

30:34.696 --> 30:35.784
[Screams]

30:35.915 --> 30:37.047
[Lestat snarling]

30:37.177 --> 30:39.701
No, stay back!

30:39.832 --> 30:41.616
[Screaming]

30:41.747 --> 30:42.922
[Gasps]

30:43.053 --> 30:44.141
[Snarls]

30:44.271 --> 30:45.794
[Grunting]

30:45.925 --> 30:47.884
♪

30:48.014 --> 30:49.581
[Screaming]

30:49.711 --> 30:52.758
[All gasping, shouting]

30:52.889 --> 30:55.195
[Moaning]

30:55.326 --> 30:56.544
[Screaming]

30:56.675 --> 30:59.199
Let's go! Let's go!

30:59.330 --> 31:01.375
[Breathing deeply]

31:01.506 --> 31:03.421
[Shouting, panting]

31:03.551 --> 31:06.815
♪

31:06.946 --> 31:08.643
It's locked![Banging on door]

31:08.774 --> 31:10.776
[Woman screams]

31:10.907 --> 31:19.959
♪

31:20.090 --> 31:29.142
♪

31:29.273 --> 31:31.014
[Screams]

31:31.144 --> 31:32.885
♪

31:33.016 --> 31:35.235
-We gotta go!
-[Sobbing]

31:35.366 --> 31:37.629
-Go to the stairs!
-[Sobbing] No!

31:37.759 --> 31:43.069
♪

31:43.200 --> 31:46.638
[Sobbing] Please...
I don't wanna die.

31:46.768 --> 31:50.207
♪

31:50.337 --> 31:52.209
[Screams]

31:52.339 --> 31:54.211
[All screaming]

31:54.341 --> 31:58.519
♪

31:58.650 --> 32:00.565
[Rasping]

32:00.695 --> 32:03.524
♪

32:03.655 --> 32:06.440
-No, no, no!
-Get up! Get up! Get up!

32:06.571 --> 32:07.789
No, no, no, no, no![Banging on window]

32:07.920 --> 32:09.530
Help! Someone help!

32:09.661 --> 32:12.403
[Brass band playing,
indistinct shouting]

32:12.533 --> 32:16.015
♪

32:16.146 --> 32:17.974
No. You don't have to do this.
Please, don't do this.

32:18.104 --> 32:20.585
Shh, shh, shh.You don't have to...
No, please.

32:20.715 --> 32:23.109
No, no, no, no, no!No, get up!

32:23.240 --> 32:25.590
[Shouting, sobbing]

32:25.720 --> 32:27.984
♪

32:28.114 --> 32:30.464
[Shouting continues]

32:30.595 --> 32:32.814
[Screaming]

32:32.945 --> 32:35.904
[Brass band playing,
people laughing in distance]

32:36.035 --> 32:45.914
♪

32:46.045 --> 32:47.351
Lestat: Oh, dear.

32:47.481 --> 32:50.136
You broke up the pair.

32:50.267 --> 32:53.966
I know you wanted them both,
but Louis couldn't resist.

32:54.097 --> 32:55.881
I'm sorry, my love.

32:56.012 --> 32:57.752
I saved one of 'em
for you.

32:57.883 --> 32:59.058
Huh.

32:59.189 --> 33:00.364
Did you?

33:02.627 --> 33:04.281
How generous of you.

33:04.411 --> 33:10.548
♪

33:10.678 --> 33:16.771
♪

33:16.902 --> 33:20.297
[Handle jiggling]

33:20.427 --> 33:22.429
[Clatters]

33:22.560 --> 33:24.562
[Laughter, chatter in distance]

33:27.173 --> 33:28.218
[Door creaks]

33:28.348 --> 33:29.784
[Laughter, chatter]

33:29.915 --> 33:32.178
[Door creaks]

33:32.309 --> 33:37.096
♪

33:37.227 --> 33:38.750
Mm.

33:38.880 --> 33:41.927
[Brass band playing,
people laughing in distance]

33:42.058 --> 33:47.933
♪

33:48.064 --> 33:49.587
Ah.

33:49.717 --> 33:58.291
♪

33:58.422 --> 34:00.119
Quite drunk, this one.

34:00.250 --> 34:05.472
♪

34:05.603 --> 34:10.869
♪

34:10.999 --> 34:12.523
Rosemary...

34:12.653 --> 34:16.092
♪

34:16.222 --> 34:17.789
...and something else.

34:17.919 --> 34:20.357
♪

34:20.487 --> 34:22.750
What is it, my love?

34:22.881 --> 34:26.450
I-I think it's the gin.

34:26.580 --> 34:28.669
I wasn't talking to you.

34:28.800 --> 34:30.323
Antoinette: Laudanum.

34:30.454 --> 34:37.330
♪

34:37.461 --> 34:39.027
Arsenic.

34:39.158 --> 34:45.208
♪

34:45.338 --> 34:47.166
She was at the ball
tonight.

34:47.297 --> 34:48.994
♪

34:49.125 --> 34:51.649
Like one of those girls
on the telephone switchboard...

34:51.779 --> 34:53.999
♪

34:54.130 --> 34:58.395
...eavesdropping in on things
that she shouldn't.

34:58.525 --> 35:03.574
"Too late.
I've done it already."

35:03.704 --> 35:06.229
"When? Who?"

35:06.359 --> 35:09.710
"Just now.
One of the twins.

35:09.841 --> 35:12.060
He'll be dead on his feet
in an hour."

35:12.191 --> 35:14.933
[Hissing]

35:15.063 --> 35:20.112
[Grunting]

35:20.243 --> 35:23.202
She should never have
been made, Louis.

35:23.333 --> 35:25.204
Look what she did to us.

35:25.335 --> 35:27.511
She's corrupted
everything.

35:27.641 --> 35:30.731
Antoinette will be much more
agreeable to our life together.

35:30.862 --> 35:32.255
[Gasps]

35:32.385 --> 35:34.561
[Grunting]

35:34.692 --> 35:36.259
[Retches]

35:36.389 --> 35:38.348
[Gasping]

35:38.478 --> 35:46.269
♪

35:46.399 --> 35:49.141
[Choking]

35:49.272 --> 35:50.751
[Shouts]
[Grunts]

35:50.882 --> 35:52.057
[Clatters]

35:52.188 --> 35:53.276
[Shouts]

35:53.406 --> 35:56.975
[Groaning]

35:57.105 --> 36:00.108
[Gasping]

36:00.239 --> 36:01.762
[Retches]

36:01.893 --> 36:04.156
♪

36:04.287 --> 36:06.071
[Whimpering]

36:06.202 --> 36:11.772
♪

36:11.903 --> 36:13.252
Lestat...

36:13.383 --> 36:15.602
♪

36:15.733 --> 36:19.432
...you must think me
an idiot.

36:19.563 --> 36:23.131
"She was at the ball
tonight."

36:23.262 --> 36:25.177
Not just the ball.

36:25.308 --> 36:26.918
Laudanum and arsenic.

36:27.048 --> 36:30.704
♪

36:30.835 --> 36:33.316
Louis: You're gonna try
to kill him at this party?

36:33.446 --> 36:35.535
Claudia:
There's no "trying."

36:35.666 --> 36:40.105
I have a plan,
and it's gonna take both of us.

36:40.236 --> 36:41.889
The train's leavin'
in an hour.

36:42.020 --> 36:43.630
Get off that bench.

36:43.761 --> 36:47.678
♪

36:47.808 --> 36:50.637
You shoulda let that train go,
Uncle Les.

36:50.768 --> 36:53.031
[Wheezing]

36:53.161 --> 36:55.120
[Gasping mockingly]

36:55.251 --> 36:59.603
♪

36:59.733 --> 37:02.954
[Gasping] How? Who?

37:03.084 --> 37:09.830
♪

37:09.961 --> 37:11.745
He who called you...

37:11.876 --> 37:13.051
"him."Him?

37:13.181 --> 37:14.748
[ Laughs ]

37:14.879 --> 37:17.490
Always the petty slights
with you, Uncle Les.

37:17.621 --> 37:19.666
[Gasping]

37:19.797 --> 37:29.023
♪

37:29.154 --> 37:30.677
Have your goodbye.

37:30.808 --> 37:36.770
♪

37:36.901 --> 37:38.816
[Grunting, blows landing]

37:38.946 --> 37:45.170
♪

37:45.301 --> 37:47.825
Louis.

37:47.955 --> 37:49.566
Louis!

37:49.696 --> 37:51.437
[Wheezing]

37:51.568 --> 37:55.136
♪

37:55.267 --> 37:58.096
Louis.

37:58.226 --> 37:59.967
Louis.

38:00.098 --> 38:04.276
[Gasping]

38:04.407 --> 38:08.193
We are joined by a cord,
by a cord that you cannot see,

38:08.324 --> 38:09.629
but it is real.

38:09.760 --> 38:11.283
It is real.

38:11.414 --> 38:20.684
♪

38:20.814 --> 38:29.997
♪

38:30.128 --> 38:31.695
I have loved you...

38:31.825 --> 38:34.828
♪

38:34.959 --> 38:36.439
...with all myself.

38:36.569 --> 38:43.881
♪

38:44.011 --> 38:51.323
♪

38:51.454 --> 38:54.457
I'm happy it was you...

38:54.587 --> 38:56.284
here with me...

38:56.415 --> 38:59.244
♪

38:59.375 --> 39:01.072
[Speaking French]

39:01.202 --> 39:06.947
♪

39:07.078 --> 39:10.386
[Choking, gasping]

39:10.516 --> 39:12.257
[Blade clatters]

39:12.388 --> 39:14.477
♪

39:14.607 --> 39:16.217
Louis:
The blood poured out of him

39:16.348 --> 39:19.090
as it might never pour
from a human being...

39:19.220 --> 39:23.747
♪

39:23.877 --> 39:25.662
[Body thuds]

39:25.792 --> 39:28.360
...all the blood he had
filled himself with.

39:28.491 --> 39:30.797
He lay now on his back,

39:30.928 --> 39:33.887
his eyes staring wildly
at the ceiling,

39:34.018 --> 39:37.369
the irises dancing
from side to side.

39:37.500 --> 39:47.379
♪

39:47.510 --> 39:57.433
♪

39:57.563 --> 40:03.656
"Mets-moi dans mon cercueil,
Louis, Louis."

40:03.787 --> 40:07.660
"Put me in my coffin,
Louis, Louis."

40:07.791 --> 40:11.621
His irises rolled
to the top of his head.

40:11.751 --> 40:15.146
The whites of his eyes
went dim.

40:15.276 --> 40:17.670
♪

40:17.801 --> 40:21.413
This horror
that had been Lestat...

40:21.544 --> 40:23.763
♪

40:23.894 --> 40:27.985
...I stared
helplessly at it.

40:28.115 --> 40:29.813
The thing lay still.

40:29.943 --> 40:32.555
♪

40:32.685 --> 40:34.426
There was no point
in lingering.

40:34.557 --> 40:36.602
♪

40:36.733 --> 40:39.431
The house on Rue Royale
would soon become the focus

40:39.562 --> 40:41.259
of all too many questions.

40:41.389 --> 40:43.522
[Indistinct conversations
in distance]

40:43.653 --> 40:51.617
♪

40:51.748 --> 40:53.706
[Banging, flames whooshing]

40:53.837 --> 40:58.058
♪

40:58.189 --> 41:00.147
[Gasps]

41:00.278 --> 41:02.541
[Screaming]

41:02.672 --> 41:09.200
♪

41:09.330 --> 41:11.376
[Screaming continues]

41:11.507 --> 41:15.249
♪

41:15.380 --> 41:17.600
For the very last time
in New Orleans,

41:17.730 --> 41:19.340
we followed our training

41:19.471 --> 41:23.910
and cleaned up the evidence
of our most elaborate kill.

41:24.041 --> 41:25.912
Well, almost.

41:26.043 --> 41:29.481
♪

41:29.612 --> 41:31.309
We need to burn him.

41:33.877 --> 41:35.966
I've killed so many,
j-just...

41:39.099 --> 41:40.710
no one I...

41:46.193 --> 41:48.848
I don't know if I can.

41:48.979 --> 41:51.895
Just load him in...

41:52.025 --> 41:53.897
like he's one of them.

41:56.029 --> 41:59.337
It was as if we'd expected
Lestat to disappear

41:59.467 --> 42:04.342
in a puff of smoke,
or get sucked back into hell.

42:04.472 --> 42:07.693
So, what did you do
with it?

42:07.824 --> 42:10.130
We wrapped him
in a carpet.

42:10.261 --> 42:12.306
We threw him in a trunk,

42:12.437 --> 42:15.875
and left him out
with the garbage.

42:16.006 --> 42:18.791
We got in our car
and drove away,

42:18.922 --> 42:21.228
headed straight
for the port.

42:21.359 --> 42:23.013
The boat for Havana?

42:23.143 --> 42:24.580
Another boat.

42:24.710 --> 42:26.233
A merchant vessel,

42:26.364 --> 42:29.410
newly christened
and headed for Europe.

42:29.541 --> 42:31.630
The boat you bought
Anderson,

42:31.761 --> 42:35.199
a shipload of coffins
for cargo.

42:35.329 --> 42:38.724
Plenty of cover
for a couple of stowaways,

42:38.855 --> 42:43.642
ready to begin the adventure
of our lives.

42:43.773 --> 42:45.296
Well...

42:45.426 --> 42:48.516
isn't that neat and tidy?

42:48.647 --> 42:50.867
There was a ship.
We did get on it.

42:50.997 --> 42:53.739
Yeah, I read that,
the first 50 pages.

42:53.870 --> 42:55.611
Not exactly the, uh,

42:55.741 --> 42:58.352
adventure-of-our-lives
feeling I'm feeling.

42:58.483 --> 43:00.572
It was
a traumatic escape.

43:00.703 --> 43:03.793
Yeah, but she didn't
say that explicitly.

43:03.923 --> 43:07.927
I mean, maybe in some of
the pages that got torn out.

43:08.058 --> 43:09.320
Well, not torn out, exactly.

43:09.450 --> 43:11.844
More like with a ruler.

43:11.975 --> 43:14.934
But, um...
there's a feeling

43:15.065 --> 43:18.024
that she hated your guts
there for a while.

43:18.155 --> 43:19.591
Why is that?

43:19.722 --> 43:23.160
I was haunted by
my brother's death,

43:23.290 --> 43:26.163
by the abandonment
of my sister,

43:26.293 --> 43:28.469
by the murder of Lestat,
I --

43:28.600 --> 43:30.820
Murder?
What murder?

43:30.950 --> 43:33.692
It was an act of mercy.

43:33.823 --> 43:35.651
You didn't kill Lestat.

43:35.781 --> 43:38.131
You spared him,
out of some fucked-up idea

43:38.262 --> 43:39.829
you had about love.

43:39.959 --> 43:41.439
[Scoffs] Love?

43:41.569 --> 43:44.311
I bled him like a pig and waited
for the death rattle.

43:44.442 --> 43:47.227
You were shot point-blank
by an alderman.

43:47.358 --> 43:49.795
You were dropped a thousand feet
and survived.

43:49.926 --> 43:54.234
You torched Antoinette
just to make sure.

43:54.365 --> 43:56.672
Where does the trash go,
Louis?

43:57.977 --> 43:59.936
♪

44:00.066 --> 44:03.069
[Both grunting]

44:03.200 --> 44:05.071
You take the trash down
to the street

44:05.202 --> 44:06.986
and some guys show up
in a truck

44:07.117 --> 44:08.379
and they throw it
in the back,

44:08.509 --> 44:09.902
and then, they drive it

44:10.033 --> 44:13.384
out to the middle
of nowhere, right?

44:13.514 --> 44:16.126
No.

44:16.256 --> 44:19.782
They take the trash
to the dump.

44:19.912 --> 44:22.480
And having lived two blocks
away from the dump

44:22.610 --> 44:26.658
just outside of Fishkill,
New York, with my first wife,

44:26.789 --> 44:31.663
I can state, with authority,
what else you'll find there.

44:31.794 --> 44:33.230
Rats.

44:33.360 --> 44:37.451
Big fuckin' rats, the size
of Kevin Durant's sneakers.

44:37.582 --> 44:39.932
Enough blood in them
to bring back the dead.

44:40.063 --> 44:45.198
Especially one in a trunk
with locks on the inside.

44:45.329 --> 44:47.200
You knew it, Louis.

44:47.331 --> 44:49.159
You had to.

44:49.289 --> 44:50.943
The biggest rat-eater
of them all.

44:51.074 --> 44:52.597
This session is over.

44:52.728 --> 44:57.123
♪

44:57.254 --> 45:00.257
How many days in
the Islamic year?

45:00.387 --> 45:03.173
How many names are there
for Allah?

45:03.303 --> 45:06.567
355, and 99.

45:06.698 --> 45:11.529
Why does a 200-pound bouncer
pass out after he sucks him off,

45:11.659 --> 45:15.359
and you, a wet T-shirt away
from 130, doesn't even blink?

45:15.489 --> 45:16.664
I couldn't burn him.

45:16.795 --> 45:17.883
But Claudia could.

45:18.014 --> 45:19.145
No, she couldn't.

45:19.276 --> 45:21.365
She stuck a pen
in his neck.

45:21.495 --> 45:25.369
She recorded his last words
in his own blood.

45:25.499 --> 45:27.458
The girl did not have
a fuckin' problem

45:27.588 --> 45:29.329
tossing him
on the grill, okay?

45:29.460 --> 45:30.548
The sun's comin' up.
No.

45:30.678 --> 45:31.767
We have to burn him.
No.

45:31.897 --> 45:33.116
It's the only way
we'll know!

45:33.246 --> 45:35.858
No!

45:35.988 --> 45:37.729
I said no!

45:37.860 --> 45:39.426
Was it raining,
Louis?

45:39.557 --> 45:40.950
She couldn't burn him.

45:41.080 --> 45:43.126
You cursed her
into the darkness.

45:43.256 --> 45:46.869
You chose Lestat over her,
time and time again.

45:46.999 --> 45:48.653
You don't need
a memoir, Louis.

45:48.784 --> 45:50.524
You need a hundred sessions
of EMDR.

45:50.655 --> 45:52.178
You know, the shit they put
soldiers through

45:52.309 --> 45:53.571
when they see one
of their platoon buddies

45:53.701 --> 45:54.790
get blown up
in front of them?

45:54.920 --> 45:56.313
You've only heard
half the story.

45:56.443 --> 45:57.531
Stop.

45:57.662 --> 45:58.968
144 years of life,

45:59.098 --> 46:01.318
and you're still
Louis the Pimp,

46:01.448 --> 46:03.711
paying a whore to sit in a room
and talk with you.

46:03.842 --> 46:05.713
'Cause why?
You got some story

46:05.844 --> 46:07.715
you wanna tell the whole world
about yourself?

46:07.846 --> 46:09.065
When you hear it,
you'll be ashamed,

46:09.195 --> 46:10.544
ashamed of what you say
to him now.

46:10.675 --> 46:11.937
Please stop, Rashid.

46:12.068 --> 46:13.896
Ten million dollars.
That's my whore number.

46:14.026 --> 46:15.549
Career's been over
for years.

46:15.680 --> 46:17.029
Legacy?

46:17.160 --> 46:19.597
That's for board members
and assholes in loafers.

46:19.727 --> 46:21.425
My daughters aren't even
speaking to me anymore,

46:21.555 --> 46:23.340
so at least I can
leave them some cash.

46:23.470 --> 46:25.864
But an honest reckoning?
No.

46:25.995 --> 46:29.389
This is the same shit
that happened in San Francisco.

46:29.520 --> 46:31.174
Not exactly.

46:31.304 --> 46:33.567
How is it
any different, Louis?

46:33.698 --> 46:35.874
This time,
I won't save your life.

46:36.005 --> 46:37.833
♪

46:37.963 --> 46:40.836
Louis can sometimes
act out.

46:40.966 --> 46:44.100
I protect him from himself,
always have.

46:44.230 --> 46:46.754
Stopped him that night
in San Francisco.

46:46.885 --> 46:48.931
♪

46:49.061 --> 46:51.237
You were there.

46:51.368 --> 46:53.979
You don't remember,
do you?

46:54.110 --> 46:57.896
No, I don't remember.

46:58.027 --> 47:01.987
What was that you said
about memory?

47:02.118 --> 47:04.729
"A monster," was it?

47:04.860 --> 47:06.992
But I saw you standing
in the sun.

47:07.123 --> 47:10.691
As we age, the sun
loses its power over us.

47:10.822 --> 47:15.348
What's a mediocre star
to a 514-year-old vampire?

47:15.479 --> 47:17.046
[Book thuds]

47:17.176 --> 47:23.791
♪

47:23.922 --> 47:30.581
♪

47:30.711 --> 47:32.061
Louis:
Daniel Malloy...

47:32.191 --> 47:33.932
♪

47:34.063 --> 47:37.240
...I'd like you to meet

47:37.370 --> 47:39.938
the vampire Armand.

47:40.069 --> 47:44.682
♪

47:44.812 --> 47:47.119
The love of my life.

47:47.250 --> 47:56.085
♪

47:56.215 --> 48:05.050
♪

48:05.181 --> 48:14.016
♪

48:14.146 --> 48:22.981
♪

48:23.112 --> 48:31.903
♪

48:32.034 --> 48:40.868
♪

48:40.999 --> 48:49.834
♪

48:49.965 --> 48:58.756
♪

48:58.886 --> 49:07.678
♪

49:07.808 --> 49:16.774
♪

49:18.689 --> 49:24.782
♪

49:24.912 --> 49:26.740
Louis: If you are really quick
it can be done,

49:26.871 --> 49:30.135
but could it be done by us
to him?

49:30.266 --> 49:33.182
Could the children
murder their father?

49:33.312 --> 49:38.622
Episode 7,
"The Thing Lay Still."

49:38.752 --> 49:40.667
We were promised the death
of Lestat,

49:40.798 --> 49:42.756
and so we must kill Lestat.

49:42.887 --> 49:45.063
Slowly, Claudia makes a pitch.

49:45.194 --> 49:48.762
Claudia: I have a plan,
and it's gonna take both of us.

49:48.893 --> 49:50.895
And she has to take
the lead because Louis

49:51.026 --> 49:54.159
is too close to Lestat
and at this point too weak.

49:54.290 --> 49:56.596
The plan only works
if he's distracted.

49:56.727 --> 49:58.468
She does what any good
plotter does.

49:58.598 --> 50:01.036
She makes it ultimately turn out
to make Lestat think

50:01.166 --> 50:02.776
that it's his idea.

50:02.907 --> 50:07.825
If we starved ourselves for a
night or several nights prior,

50:07.955 --> 50:11.437
the hunger
would be transcendent.

50:11.568 --> 50:13.439
A meal fit for a king.

50:13.570 --> 50:16.007
To get Lestat
at his most egoistical

50:16.138 --> 50:18.531
and his most blinded,
yes, maybe then

50:18.662 --> 50:21.056
I will buy this idea
to lets go out with a bang.

50:21.186 --> 50:23.449
Let's not be these hiding,
shrieking vampires.

50:23.580 --> 50:25.625
Let's leave rooms full of bodies
and get on out

50:25.756 --> 50:27.801
on the last train.

50:27.932 --> 50:30.804
But Louis, you got to open
your heart back up to him.

50:30.935 --> 50:34.156
That is the thing that will
blind Lestat more than anything.

50:34.286 --> 50:37.028
A last dance
before the feast.

50:37.159 --> 50:40.336
It is the swooning heights
of the uber romanticism

50:40.466 --> 50:43.252
of ours is this dance in front
of everybody and this kiss.

50:43.382 --> 50:44.775
Lestat cannot help himself.

50:44.905 --> 50:46.168
He's so in love with Louis.

50:46.298 --> 50:47.517
But in the middle of the party,

50:47.647 --> 50:49.127
we are picking our victims out.

50:49.258 --> 50:50.650
We're gonna have the great feast

50:50.781 --> 50:52.391
of our life,
so it can't just be one victim.

50:52.522 --> 50:54.480
It's gonna be like one of these
horrible tasting menus

50:54.611 --> 50:56.221
where we're just gonna gather up
all these people

50:56.352 --> 50:58.615
that know we have
the fountain of youth

50:58.745 --> 51:00.704
and come back to our
after party.

51:00.834 --> 51:03.185
Would you like to know
the secret of immortality?

51:03.315 --> 51:05.622
Well, of course, my dear.
Who wouldn't?

51:05.752 --> 51:08.842
There they are, but they are
there only as the grand plan,

51:08.973 --> 51:11.280
get Lestat looking this way
and now we have

51:11.410 --> 51:12.585
a little bit of fun.

51:12.716 --> 51:13.630
Give me that ladle.

51:13.760 --> 51:16.067
♪

51:16.198 --> 51:17.721
It's empty.

51:17.851 --> 51:19.897
Not for long, Tom.

51:20.027 --> 51:21.725
[Screams]

51:21.855 --> 51:23.205
Most of them are sort
of the ugly ones

51:23.335 --> 51:24.771
that we have seen
throughout the show,

51:24.902 --> 51:26.338
but then, look at the twins.

51:26.469 --> 51:27.905
We all know the books.

51:28.035 --> 51:28.993
Go to the twins,
go to the twins.

51:29.124 --> 51:31.517
You broke up the pair.

51:31.648 --> 51:35.304
I know you wanted them both,
but Louis couldn't resist.

51:35.434 --> 51:37.349
I'm sorry, my love.

51:37.480 --> 51:40.309
And then there's this mysterious
man in the tuxedo.

51:40.439 --> 51:43.442
What is that all about? Very
strange little detail there.

51:43.573 --> 51:44.878
And, you know,
you guys are all savvy.

51:45.009 --> 51:46.576
You know something's
not right here.

51:46.706 --> 51:49.883
I can't be that easy, until you
had that reverse line.

51:50.014 --> 51:53.757
I've always known Antoinette
was out there.

51:53.887 --> 51:56.194
So, if you played everybody's
sort of arcs,

51:56.325 --> 51:58.544
no one quite knew everything.

51:58.675 --> 52:01.721
How? Who?

52:01.852 --> 52:03.114
Jones: Claudia knew
that eventually

52:03.245 --> 52:05.595
if we put Tom Anderson in there,
make him drink

52:05.725 --> 52:07.858
poison blood,
he would go after Tom Anderson.

52:07.988 --> 52:09.816
He who called you him.

52:09.947 --> 52:12.428
Him? [Laughs]

52:12.558 --> 52:14.560
They don't quite know totally
how to kill a vampire,

52:14.691 --> 52:16.693
but they think
that'll do the job.

52:16.823 --> 52:19.304
Always the petty sights
with you, Uncle Les.

52:19.435 --> 52:20.566
[Gasping]

52:20.697 --> 52:23.830
♪

52:23.961 --> 52:26.746
Back to Dubai, Molloy
starts asking questions

52:26.877 --> 52:28.705
and some very probing questions.

52:28.835 --> 52:31.447
What actually did happen
that night?

